'''Asa'pili''' is a [[constructed language]] created by the pseudonymous author [[P.M._(author)|P.M.]] in his book [[Bolo'bolo]]. On the one hand, it is an [[artistic language]], intended to explain his concepts for a sustainable future in an original way. On the other hand, it is a neutral [[International auxiliary language|auxiliary language]] intended for use in the quasi-utopian ''bolo''-based global community which he describes in the book. Asa'pili is not a full language, but a basic vocabulary of about thirty words, which can be used to refer to cultural institutions and concepts.
The complete list of the basic words is as follows:
{| class="wikitable" ! Glyph ! Pronunciation ! Meaning |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-ibu.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''ibu'']]||align="center"|ibu||"individual, person" |- ||[[File:Bolo-glyph bolo'bolo P M.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''bolo'']]||align="center"|bolo||"community, village, tribe" (basic autonomous social unit of 300-500 persons) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-sila.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''sila'']]||align="center"|sila||"hospitality, tolerance, mutual aid" (includes individual rights to ''taku'', ''yalu'', ''gano'', ''bete'', ''fasi'', ''nima'', ''yaka'', and ''nugo'') |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-taku.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''taku'']]||align="center"|taku||"personal property, secret" (right of each person to keep a footlocker of 0.25 cubic meters for inviolable storage of personal possessions; everything else is ultimately communal) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-kana.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''kana'']]||align="center"|kana||"household, hunting party, family, gang" (close-knit group of 15–30 people within a ''bolo'') |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-nima.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''nima'']]||align="center"|nima||"way of life, tradition, culture" (also, the right to practice and advocate for one's chosen way of life) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-kodu.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''kodu'']]||align="center"|kodu||"agriculture, nature, sustenance" (predominantly local — many ''bolo''s are to be self-sufficient in basic foodstuffs) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-yalu.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''yalu'']]||align="center"|yalu||"food, cuisine" (predominantly prepared in units larger than nuclear-family households from locally grown supplies) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-sibi.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''sibi'']]||align="center"|sibi||"craft, art, industry" (oriented towards skilled handicraft methods, rather than mass production, with frequent personal relationships between individual makers and those who use their products) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-pali.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''pali'']]||align="center"|pali||"energy, fuel" (local self-sufficiency lessens the need for high resource consumption) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-sufu.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''suvu'']]||align="center"|suvu||"water, water supply, well, baths" |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-gano.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''gano'']]||align="center"|gano||"house, building, dwelling" (isolated single-family dwellings will be replaced by less wasteful buildings for ''kana''s or ''bolo''s) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-bete.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''bete'']]||align="center"|bete||"medicine, health" |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-nugo.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''nugo'']]||align="center"|nugo||"death, suicide pill" (every ''ibu'' has the right to commit suicide at any time, or to request aid in committing suicide if unable to do so on their own) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-pili.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''pili'']]||align="center"|pili||"communication, education, language, media" (no centralized educational curricula or one-way mass-media) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-kene.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''kene'']]||align="center"|kene||"communal work" (localized initiatives to mobilize labor to accomplish necessary public tasks) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-tega.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''tega'']]||align="center"|tega||"district, town" (loose self-governing affiliation of from ten to twenty ''bolo''s) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-dala.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''dala'']]||align="center"|dala||"council, assembly" (forum for discussion and settlement of issues larger than a single ''bolo'') |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-dudi.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''dudi'']]||align="center"|dudi||"foreigner, observer" (external delegates who participate in ''dala''s outside their own district or region) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-fudo.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''vudo'']]||align="center"|vudo||"city, county, trading area, bioregion" (about 400 ''bolo''s) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-sumi.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''sumi'']]||align="center"|sumi||"region, linguistic area, island" (about twenty to thirty ''vudo''s, the "largest practical unity") |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-asa.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''asa'']]||align="center"|asa||"earth, world" |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-buni.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''buni'']]||align="center"|buni||"gift, present" (informal exchange of goods which largely replaces commercial trade) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-mafa.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''mafa'']]||align="center"|mafa||"depot, warehouse" (organized reserves of basic items in case of collective or individual need) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-feno.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''feno'']]||align="center"|feno||"barter agreement, trade relation" (more strictly reciprocal than gifts) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-sadi.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''sadi'']]||align="center"|sadi||"market, stock market, fair" (commercial trade for high-value or non-local items, has a limited role in the overall economy) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-fasi.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''fasi'']]||align="center"|fasi||"travel, transport, traffic, nomadism" (the right to travel everywhere at will; however, most travel will be local by low-energy methods) |- ||[[File:Bologlyph-yaka.svg|30px|center|Symbol of ''yaka'']]||align="center"|yaka||"disagreement, war, duel" (the right to challenge other individuals or communities to a duel or melee under specified terms) |- |||align="center"|munu||"reputation" (more important than money in being able to cooperate productively with others) |}
All these terms (except ''munu'') are accompanied by corresponding abstract glyphs,<ref>[http://www.lyber-eclat.net/lyber/bolo/asapili.html Lyber-eclat.net]</ref> so that the concepts can be represented visually independently of any specific writing system. These words can be combined into modifier-modified compounds (with the two elements separated by an apostrophe), so that ''asa'pili'' means "world language", ''fasi'ibu'' means "traveler", ''vudo'dala'' means "county-level assembly", etc. Doubling a noun changes it into a collective or abstract noun, so that ''bolo'bolo'' means "all ''bolo''s, the system of ''bolo''s".
