{{Infobox language |name=Koraga |nativename= ಕೊರಗ |states=[[India]] |ethnicity=[[Koraga people|Koraga]] |speakers=14,000 Korra Koraga |date=2007 census |ref=e18 |script=[[Kannada script]] |familycolor=Dravidian |fam2=Southern Dravidian |fam3=Tulu |lc1=kfd|ld1=Korra Koraga |lc2=vmd|ld2=Mudu Koraga |glotto=kora1289 |glottorefname=Koraga }}
'''Koraga''' (also rendered ''Koragar, Koragara, Korangi)'' is a [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian language]] spoken by the [[Koraga people]], a [[Scheduled tribe]] people of [[Dakshina Kannada]], [[Karnataka]], and [[Kerala]] in South West [[India]]. The dialect spoken by the Koraga tribe in Kerala, Mudu Koraga, is divergent enough to not be intelligible with Korra Koraga.{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|p=2}}
==Classification== Koraga is a member of the [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] family of languages.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fairservis |first=Walter Ashlin |title=The Harappan Civilization and Its Writing: A Model for the Decipherment of the Indus Script |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |series = Asian Studies |year=1997 |isbn=978-90-04-09066-8 |page=16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Stassen |first=Leon |title=Intransitive Predication |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |series = Oxford Studies in Typology and Linguistic Theory |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-19-925893-2 |page=220 }}</ref> It is further classified into the Southern Dravidian family. Koraga is a spoken language and generally not written, whenever it is written it makes use of Kannada script. Koraga people are generally conversant in [[Tulu language|Tulu]]{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|p=4}} and [[Kannada]] languages and hence use those languages as a medium for producing literature.
==Dialects== According to {{harvtxt|Bhat|1971}}, there are 4 dialects:{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|p=2}} *''Onti'' (spoken in [[Udupi]]) *''Tappu'' (in [[Hebri]]) *''Mudu'' (in [[Kundapura]]) *''Ande'' (midway between ''tappu'' and ''onti'' and in [[Mangalore]])
All the speakers who speak ''Mudu'' dialect are bilingual with Kannada language and all speaking ''onti'' dialect are bilingual with Tulu language.{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|p=2}} This has resulted a strong influence of Kannada on Mudu koraga and also similar influence of Tulu is seen on onti koraga dialect.{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|pp=2 ,4}} Majority of negative forms of onti koraga language are borrowed from Tulu language.{{sfnp|Bhat|1971|p=45}}
