{{Infobox language |name=Koschneiderisch |states = |region = |speakers=? |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] |fam3=[[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] |fam4=[[Low German]] |fam5=[[East Low German]] |fam6=[[East Pomeranian dialect|East Pomeranian]] |isoexception= |glotto= |glottoname= |glottorefname= }}
'''Koschneiderisch''' is a part of [[East Low German]] [[East Pomeranian dialect]] that is either moribund or used to be spoken in [[Pomerania]] (now Northwestern [[Poland]], previously part of [[Germany]]). It is part of the [[Low German language]]. In or shortly after [[World War II]], the Koschneiderisch-speaking German inhabitants of the region were largely [[Expulsion of Germans after World War II|expelled]] to western [[Germany]]. It has [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalization]] of the ''k''-sound, resulting in a sound similar to the ''ć''-sound of the [[Polish language]]. <ref name="auto">''Die Orts- und Flurnamen der Koschneiderei'', Danziger Verlags-Gesellschaft, Danzig, 1926, p. 29</ref> Koschneiderisch includes a limited number of [[High German languages|High German]] words. <ref name="auto"/>
